<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>When Nixon ended the Bretton Woods system in 1971, what was the immediate effect?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">The dollar was no longer convertible to gold</option>
            <option letter="b">The dollar became stronger</option>
            <option letter="c">Interest rates fell dramatically</option>
            <option letter="d">International trade stopped</option>
        </options>
        <answer>a</answer>
        <explanation>Nixon's closure of the "gold window" meant foreign governments could no longer exchange their dollars for gold at the fixed rate of $35 per ounce.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>How do T-accounts show a bank's loan creation?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Only the asset side increases</option>
            <option letter="b">Only the liability side increases</option>
            <option letter="c">Both sides increase equally</option>
            <option letter="d">Neither side changes</option>
        </options>
        <answer>c</answer>
        <explanation>When a bank creates a loan, both sides of the T-account increase equally - the loan as an asset and the new deposit as a liability.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>Which Federal Reserve function came from the Free Silver Movement era?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Being the lender of last resort</option>
            <option letter="b">Setting reserve requirements</option>
            <option letter="c">Managing the gold standard</option>
            <option letter="d">Printing Federal Reserve Notes</option>
        </options>
        <answer>a</answer>
        <explanation>The concept of a central bank as lender of last resort emerged partly in response to the financial instability that drove the Free Silver Movement.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>What distinguishes fiat money from commodity money?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Fiat money has no intrinsic value</option>
            <option letter="b">Fiat money is always gold-backed</option>
            <option letter="c">Fiat money cannot be paper</option>
            <option letter="d">Fiat money must be metallic</option>
        </options>
        <answer>a</answer>
        <explanation>Fiat money has value only because of government decree and public trust, unlike commodity money which has intrinsic value.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>During the gold standard era, what happened when new gold was discovered?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">The money supply increased</option>
            <option letter="b">The money supply decreased</option>
            <option letter="c">The money supply stayed constant</option>
            <option letter="d">Banks stopped making loans</option>
        </options>
        <answer>a</answer>
        <explanation>Under the gold standard, new gold discoveries led to increases in the money supply as the new gold entered the monetary system.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
